### Achievements

#### Law of definite proportions

Upon his arrival in [Stockholm](/Stockholm), one of Berzelius's initial, yet remarkably impactful, undertakings was the authorship of a [chemistry](/Chemistry) textbook intended for his medical students. This work, titled *Lärbok i Kemien*, marked his inaugural significant scientific publication. The textbook itself was not merely a compilation of existing knowledge; it was underpinned by Berzelius's own extensive experimental work on the compositions of [inorganic compounds](/Inorganic_compounds), representing his earliest forays into the concept of definite proportions.

Between 1813 and 1814, he meticulously compiled and submitted a comprehensive essay, eventually published across five distinct articles, detailing the precise proportions of elements within compounds. This monumental essay commenced with a broad, overarching description of his findings, before introducing his novel system of [chemical notation](/Chemical_formula). It then proceeded to methodically examine every known element of the time, a task of immense empirical scope. The culmination of this detailed exposition was a table presenting the "specific weights" (which we now understand as relative [atomic masses](/Atomic_weight)) of the elements, with [oxygen](/Oxygen) arbitrarily set to a value of 100, followed by a selection of compounds meticulously written in his newly devised formalism. This rigorous body of work provided compelling, undeniable evidence in support of the [atomic theory](/Atomic_theory) that had been put forth by [John Dalton](/John_Dalton). Specifically, it demonstrated with empirical clarity that [inorganic chemical compounds](/Inorganic_compound) are not random agglomerations but are instead composed of atoms of different elements combined in precise, reproducible [whole number amounts](/Whole_number_rule).

In a rather elegant scientific twist, Berzelius's detailed analysis also served to effectively disprove [Prout's hypothesis](/Prout%27s_hypothesis), which posited that all elements were simply built up from integer multiples of the atomic weight of [hydrogen](/Hydrogen). His findings unequivocally showed that [atomic weights](/Atomic_weight) were not, in fact, always integer multiples of [hydrogen](/Hydrogen)'s weight. The final, revised iteration of his [atomic weight](/Atomic_weight) tables, a testament to his persistent refinement of data, was first unveiled in a [German](/German_language) translation of his *Textbook of Chemistry* in 1826.

#### Chemical notation

To streamline his experiments and, perhaps more importantly, to bring some much-needed order to the increasingly complex world of [chemistry](/Chemistry), Berzelius conceived and developed a revolutionary system of [chemical notation](/Chemical_formula). This ingenious system assigned simple, concise written labels to the elements that constituted any given [chemical compound](/Chemical_compound)—for instance, 'O' for [oxygen](/Oxygen), or 'Fe' for [iron](/Iron). Their respective proportions within the compound were then indicated by numerical values. In essence, Berzelius single-handedly invented the system of [chemical notation](/Chemical_formula) that, with only minor modifications, remains universally employed today. The primary divergence from modern practice lies in his initial preference for [superscripts](/Superscripts) (e.g., H²O or Fe²O³) to denote the number of atoms, whereas contemporary chemists, opting for a slightly less visually elevated style, now predominantly utilize subscripts (H₂O or Fe₂O₃). A small change, but one that perhaps speaks volumes about the evolving aesthetic sensibilities of the scientific community.

#### Discovery of elements

Berzelius is widely recognized for his discovery of the [chemical elements](/Chemical_element) [cerium](/Cerium) and [selenium](/Selenium). Beyond mere discovery, he also holds the distinction of being the first to successfully isolate [silicon](/Silicon), [thorium](/Thorium), [titanium](/Titanium), and [zirconium](/Zirconium)—a rather impressive haul for one individual. He unearthed [cerium](/Cerium) in 1803, bringing another piece to the growing puzzle of the periodic table, and followed this feat with the discovery of [selenium](/Selenium) in 1817. His pioneering work in isolation continued with [silicon](/Silicon) in 1824, and [thorium](/Thorium) also in 1824. It's worth noting that the intellectual vibrancy of Berzelius's laboratory environment was such that his own students, working under his guidance, went on to discover [lithium](/Lithium), [lanthanum](/Lanthanum), and [vanadium](/Vanadium), demonstrating the profound impact of his mentorship.

His discovery of amorphous [silicon](/Silicon) stemmed from a methodical repetition of an earlier experiment conducted by [Gay-Lussac](/Joseph-Louis_Gay-Lussac) and [Thénard](/Louis_Jacques_Th%C3%A9nard). In their initial attempt, they reacted [silicon tetrafluoride](/Silicon_tetrafluoride) with [potassium](/Potassium) metal, a process that yielded a rather impure form of [silicon](/Silicon). Berzelius, ever the perfectionist, introduced a variation: he heated [potassium fluorosilicate](/Potassium_fluorosilicate) with [potassium](/Potassium). This produced [potassium silicide](/Potassium_silicide), which he then carefully stirred with water to obtain a comparatively pure [silicon](/Silicon) powder. Berzelius, with characteristic insight, immediately recognized this powder as a distinct new element, which he christened "silicium," a name that had, coincidentally, been proposed earlier by [Humphry Davy](/Humphry_Davy).

While Berzelius was the first to isolate [zirconium](/Zirconium) in 1824, achieving a relatively pure sample, the truly pure form of the element remained elusive for over a century, finally being produced in 1925 by [Anton Eduard van Arkel](/Anton_Eduard_van_Arkel) and [Jan Hendrik de Boer](/Jan_Hendrik_de_Boer). Such is the often protracted journey from discovery to ultimate purity in the world of elements.

#### New chemical terms

Volumes I-III of Lärbok i kemien

Berzelius, with a flair for nomenclature, is widely credited with coining several indispensable chemical terms that continue to populate scientific discourse today. These include "[catalysis](/Catalysis)," "[polymer](/Polymer)," "[isomer](/Isomer)," "[protein](/Protein)," and "[allotrope](/Allotropy)." It's a curious historical footnote, however, that his initial definitions for some of these terms diverged rather significantly from their modern interpretations. As a case in point, he introduced the term "[polymer](/Polymer)" in 1833. His intention was to describe [organic compounds](/Organic_compounds) that, despite possessing identical [empirical formulas](/Empirical_formula), exhibited differences in their overall molecular weight. Under his original framework, the larger of these compounds would be designated as "polymers" of the smallest. This definition, while logical within the scientific understanding of his time, predated the development of the concept of [chemical structure](/Chemical_structure). Consequently, his focus remained solely on the numbers of atoms of each element present. This led him to categorize, for example, [glucose](/Glucose) (C₆H₁₂O₆) as a "[polymer](/Polymer)" of [formaldehyde](/Formaldehyde) (CH₂O), an assertion we now understand to be structurally incorrect, as [glucose](/Glucose) is decidedly not a [polymer](/Polymer) of the [monomer](/Monomer) [formaldehyde](/Formaldehyde). A reminder that even the most brilliant minds operate within the constraints of their contemporary knowledge.

#### Biology and organic chemistry

Berzelius was, notably, the first individual to draw a clear and crucial distinction between [organic compounds](/Organic_compounds)—those intricate molecules containing [carbon](/Carbon)—and [inorganic compounds](/Inorganic_compounds), which typically lack this fundamental element. This classification was a significant conceptual leap, laying groundwork for the specialized fields of [organic](/Organic_chemistry) and [inorganic chemistry](/Inorganic_chemistry). His influence extended to guiding [Gerardus Johannes Mulder](/Gerardus_Johannes_Mulder) in his meticulous [elemental analyses](/Elemental_analysis) of complex [organic compounds](/Organic_compounds) found in everyday life, such as [coffee](/Coffee), [tea](/Tea), and various [proteins](/Protein). Indeed, the very term "[protein](/Protein)" itself was coined by Berzelius in 1838. This came about after Mulder observed that all [proteins](/Protein) appeared to share a remarkably similar [empirical formula](/Empirical_formula), leading him to the (erroneous) conclusion that they might all be composed of a single, colossal type of [molecule](/Molecule). Berzelius, recognizing the profound significance of these substances, derived the term from the [Greek](/Ancient_Greek) word meaning "of the first rank," proposing it precisely because [proteins](/Protein) were so fundamentally vital to living organisms. A moment of accidental prescience, perhaps, given the later understanding of their immense biological importance.

In an early contribution to biological [chemistry](/Chemistry), Berzelius made the interesting discovery in 1808 that [lactic acid](/Lactic_acid) was not exclusively found in milk, as previously thought, but also occurred naturally within muscle tissue. A small detail, perhaps, but one that hinted at the complex biochemical processes occurring within living bodies.

He also, in 1840, coined the term "[biliverdin](/Biliverdin)," though he personally favored "bilifulvin" (referring to its yellow/red hue) over "bilirubin" (its red counterpart). The subtleties of pigment nomenclature, truly thrilling stuff.

#### Vitalism

Volumes 4-6 of Lärbok i kemien , titled Lärbok i organiska kemien

In 1810, Berzelius articulated a belief that living organisms operated under the influence of some enigmatic "vital force." This hypothesis, known as [vitalism](/Vitalism), was not entirely original, having been proposed by earlier researchers, but Berzelius gave it his own distinct flavor. He contended that [compounds](/Chemical_compound) could be definitively categorized based on whether their [synthesis](/Biosynthesis) required the involvement of living organisms ([organic compounds](/Organic_compounds)) or if they could be formed independently ([inorganic compounds](/Inorganic_compounds)). This seemed like a neat, albeit rather mystical, way to draw a line in the sand.

However, the universe, with its usual disregard for elegant theories, had other plans. In 1828, [Friedrich Wöhler](/Friedrich_W%C3%B6hler), a former student of Berzelius, quite accidentally managed to synthesize [urea](/Urea)—a quintessential [organic compound](/Organic_compound)—simply by heating [ammonium cyanate](/Ammonium_cyanate), a decidedly [inorganic](/Inorganic_chemistry) precursor. This serendipitous discovery was a rather inconvenient truth for the vitalists; it demonstrated unequivocally that an [organic compound](/Organic_compound) like [urea](/Urea) could be prepared synthetically, without the mystical intervention of a "vital force" from living organisms. Berzelius, ever the pragmatist, corresponded with Wöhler on these revolutionary findings. Yet, the tenacious notion of [vitalism](/Vitalism) proved remarkably resilient, refusing to simply vanish after a single experiment. It continued to cling to scientific thought until a substantial body of further work on the abiotic [synthesis](/Biosynthesis) of other [organic compounds](/Organic_compound) gradually provided overwhelming evidence, finally rendering [vitalism](/Vitalism) an interesting, if ultimately incorrect, historical footnote in the grand narrative of [chemistry](/Chemistry).

